y, and the future of CoN.</span><hr size=1> To answer your question Lohki, I'll repost from the members section of my guild message board:<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Here's some history:<br>
<br>
&quot;I was laid off from my job as a help desk analyst with Verizon back in February. Since then, I've sent numerous resumes out...and have had one.....*one* interview. The field is shrinking with each new round of layoffs by companies in my area.<br>
<br>
In light of this, I have managed to exhaust my savings, my stocks, my unemployment. I made the last mortgage payment I could make for this month. My phone rings with collections about my car etc. Not a pretty picture.<br>
<br>
I have contacted a real estate agent who is confident that she can rent my house out for the mortgage value, if not $100 more. If she can find a renter between now and Nov 15th, then I'll be here till at least January (delayed enlistment). <br>
<br>
If she cannot, I can head to basic as soon as 2 weeks from now..or a bit longer.<br>
<br>
I do this for a few reasons, one that is most important is my son.<br>
<br>
He lives with his mother, who has been more than gracious in not asking for child support during my struggle to get a job, keep my house...etc. He deserves good benefits, and a father he can be proud of.<br>
<br>
 By joining the Navy, I open a world of opportunity for myself. The pay is ok, but everthing is free while active just about...the housing, uniforms, even can get food allowances etc. I can also earn more credits toward college....college that I never finished due to life requiring me to work to support myself.<br>
<br>
I'm 31 years old, and a bit unnerved at the prospect of having to leave this wonderful son of mine for extended periods of time...but its for him that I do this first and foremost...then myself. I love my country, and I love my son, and perhaps in my service to the United States of America, I can be able to serve and protect both equally.&quot;<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Everything I've done in life I've &quot;lucked&quot; into for the most part. I wasnt a very good student, failed out of college more than once...finally had a job I was good at, but then was let go. I dont have a feeling of accomplishment. This being unemployed is a hell like no other...I cant begin to tell you of the nights I hardly slept, wondering about how the hell I was going to pay my bills. Part time or full time work at a mall or such cant begin to cover the amount of debt I have at this time...and all of which is just damn bad timing. Trust me when I say I've tried everything to keep going.<br>
<br>
When the opportunity arose to join the Navy, I jumped. Its guaranteed benefits for my son, and training that would cost tons in the civilian world. Once in I can train in many fields, therefore broadening my value when I get out.<br>
<br>
